{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491105","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491105"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:32:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:32:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"832"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"832","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/832"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.01,0.05,0.68,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"832"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90522"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"832","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/832"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"832"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74762"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"347"},{"type":"tags","id":"1181"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1038"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31050"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90522","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/90522"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 28-year-old woman presents with a three week history of a painless swelling in her neck. She is otherwise in good health and never had any previous problems with neck swellings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EExamination shows a 3cm diameter non-tender subcutaneous swelling immediately anterior to the left sternomastoid muscle. The swelling is compressible and is situated about one third of the distance up from the sternum to the angle of the jaw. No other abnormalities are found in the head or neck.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Thyroglossal cyst","Metastatic squamous cell carcinoma","Cystic hygroma","Branchial cyst","Epidermoid cyst"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe swelling Is compressible and therefore contains fluid. The described anatomical position of the swelling fits exactly for a \u003Cstrong\u003Ebranchial cyst\u003C/strong\u003E. These congenital lesions frequently do not become apparent until the third or fourth decades of life.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThyroglossal cysts\u003C/strong\u003E are typically found in the anterior mid-line.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetastatic squamous cell carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E from a mucosal head and neck primary site produces cystic lymphadenopathy which can mimic a benign cyst. It is increasingly common in younger patients and US-guided FNA is important to exclude a malignancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ecystic hygroma\u003C/strong\u003E is a congenital malformation of the lymphatic system and usually presents in children younger than two years. Whilst these swellings can present in adulthood, the individual would almost certainly have been aware of a swelling in this region on previous occasions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEpidermoid cysts\u003C/strong\u003E are often found in the neck, although usually on the nape of the neck. As these cysts contain sebaceous material, they are not readily compressible.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Branchial cysts typically do not become evident until the third or fourth decades of life."],"references":["Brown RE, Harave S. Diagnostic imaging of benign and malignant neck masses in children\u2014a pictorial review. Quant Imaging Med Surg 2016; 6:591-604."]},"relationships":{"itemRevisi